# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: modbus-protocol
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:modbus-protocol/modbus] Modbus is popular in industrial environments because it is openly published and royalty-free.
[src:modbus-protocol/modbus] It was developed for industrial applications, is relatively easy to deploy and maintain compared to other standards, and places few restrictions on the format of the data to be transmitted.
[src:modbus-protocol/modbus] The Modbus protocol uses serial communication lines, Ethernet, or the Internet protocol suite as a transport layer.
[src:modbus-protocol/modbus] Modbus supports communication to and from multiple devices connected to the same cable or Ethernet network.
[src:modbus-protocol/modbus] For example, there can be a device that measures temperature and another device to measure humidity connected to the same cable, both communicating measurements to the same computer, via Modbus.
[src:modbus-protocol/modbus] Modbus is often used to connect a plant/system supervisory computer with a remote terminal unit (RTU) in supervisory control and data acquisition (SCADA) systems.
[src:modbus-protocol/modbus] Many of the data types are named from industrial control of factory devices, such as ladder logic because of its use in driving relays: a single-bit physical output is called a *coil*, and a single-bit physical input is called a *discrete input* or a *contact*.
[src:modbus-protocol/modbus] It was originally published in 1979 by Modicon (bought by Schneider Electric in 1997).
[src:modbus-protocol/modbus] In 2004, they transferred the rights to the Modbus Organization which is a trade association of users and suppliers of Modbus-compliant devices that advocates for the continued use of the technology.
[src:modbus-protocol/modbus] To support Modbus communication on a network, many modems and gateways incorporate proprietary designs (refer to the diagram: *Architecture of a network for Modbus communication*).
[src:modbus-protocol/modbus] Implementations may deploy either wireline or wireless communication, such as in the ISM radio band, and even Short Message Service (SMS) or General Packet Radio Service (GPRS).
[src:modbus-protocol/modbus] Modbus defines a *client* which is an entity that initiates a transaction to request any specific task from its *request receiver*.
[src:modbus-protocol/modbus] The client's "request receiver", which the client has initiated the transaction with, is then called the *server*.
[src:modbus-protocol/modbus] For example, when a microcontroller connects to a sensor to read its data by Modbus on a wired network, e.g RS485 bus, the MCU in this context is the client and the sensor is the server.
[src:modbus-protocol/modbus] In former terminology, the client was named master and the server named slave.
[src:modbus-protocol/modbus] Modbus defines a protocol data unit (PDU) independently to its lower layer protocols in its protocol stack.
[src:modbus-protocol/modbus] Mapping MODBUS protocol on specific buses or networks requires some additional fields, defined as the application data unit (ADU).
[src:modbus-protocol/modbus] The ADU is formed by a *client* inside a Modbus network when the client initiates a transaction.
[src:modbus-protocol/modbus] The ADU is officially called a *Modbus frame* by the Modbus Organization, although *frame* is used as the data unit in the data-link layer in the OSI and TCP/IP model (while Modbus is an application layer protocol).
[src:modbus-protocol/modbus] ADU max size on RS232/RS485 network is 256 bytes, and with TCP is 260 bytes.
[src:modbus-protocol/modbus] For data encoding, Modbus uses a big-endian representation for addresses and data fields.
[src:modbus-protocol/modbus] Thus, for a 16-bit value, the most significant byte is sent first.
[src:modbus-protocol/modbus] For example, when a 16-bit register has value 0x1234, byte 0x12 is sent before byte 0x34.
[src:modbus-protocol/modbus] The data field of the PDU has the address from 0 to 65535 (not to be confused with the address of the Additional address field of ADU).
[src:modbus-protocol/modbus] The data field of the PDU can be empty, and then has a size of 0.
[src:modbus-protocol/modbus] In this case, the server will not request any information and the function code defines the function to be executed.
[src:modbus-protocol/modbus] If there is no error during the execution process, the data field of the ADU response from server to client will include the data requested, i.e. the data the client previously received.
[src:modbus-protocol/modbus] If there is any error, the server will respond with an exception code.
[src:modbus-protocol/modbus] field's size depends on the function code and usually includes values like variable values, data offset, and sub-function codes.
[src:modbus-protocol/modbus] is equal to the Function code, except that its MSB is set to 1.
[src:modbus-protocol/modbus] For each of the primary tables, the protocol allows individual selection of 65536 data items, and the operations of read or write of those items are designed to span multiple consecutive data items up to a data size limit which is dependent on the transaction function code.
[src:modbus-protocol/modbus] Modbus defines three types of function codes: Public, User-Defined and Reserved.
[src:modbus-protocol/modbus] Note: Some sources use terminology that differs from the standard; for example *Force Single Coil* instead of *Write Single Coil*.
[src:modbus-protocol/modbus] On a successful execution, mb_rsp_pdu will return one byte to note the function code (0x01), followed by one byte to indicate the number of data bytes it is returning (n), which will be the number of coils requested by mb_req_pdu, divided by 8 bits per byte, and rounded up.
[src:modbus-protocol/modbus] The remainder of the response will be the specified number (n) of data bytes.
[src:modbus-protocol/modbus] Starting Address (2 bytes) is 0x0013, (or 19 in decimal) which is the 20th coil.
[src:modbus-protocol/modbus] Quantity of Outputs (2 bytes) is 0x0013, (or 19 in decimal) which corresponds to 19 values of status of coils 20th to 38th.
[src:modbus-protocol/modbus] As 19 coils (20-38) are required, 3 bytes is used to indicate the coil's state.
[src:modbus-protocol/modbus] States of coil from 20 to 27 is 0xCD, which is 1100 1101 in binary.
[src:modbus-protocol/modbus] With coil from 36 to 38, the state will be 0x05, which is 0000 0101.
[src:modbus-protocol/modbus] Coil 38 state is the 3rd bit (count from the right), i.e 1, coil 37 is 0, and coil 36 state is LSb bit, i.e.
[src:modbus-protocol/modbus] User-Defined Function Codes are function codes defined by users.
[src:modbus-protocol/modbus] Modbus gives two range of values for user-defined function codes: 65 to 72 and 100 to 110.
[src:modbus-protocol/modbus] Obviously, user-defined function codes are not unique.
[src:modbus-protocol/modbus] Reserved Function Codes are function codes used by some companies for legacy product and are not available for public use.
[src:modbus-protocol/modbus] Modbus standard also defines Modbus over Serial Line, a protocol over the data link layer of the OSI model for the Modbus application layer protocol to be communicated over a serial bus.
[src:modbus-protocol/modbus] Modbus Serial Line protocol is a master-slave protocol which supports one master and multiple slaves in the serial bus.
[src:modbus-protocol/modbus] With Modbus protocol on the application layer, client/server model is used for the devices on the communication channel.
[src:modbus-protocol/modbus] With Modbus over Serial Line, *client*'s role is implemented by *master*, and the *server*'s role is implemented by *slave*.
[src:modbus-protocol/modbus] The organization's naming convention inverts the common usage of having multiple clients and only one server.
[src:modbus-protocol/modbus] To avoid this confusion, the RS-485 transport layer uses the terms "node" or "device" instead of "server", and the "client" is not a "node".
[src:modbus-protocol/modbus] A serial bus for Modbus over Serial Line can have a maximum of 247 slaves communicating with one master.
[src:modbus-protocol/modbus] Those slaves have a unique address ranging from 1 to 247 (01hex to F7hex).
[src:modbus-protocol/modbus] The addresses from 248 to 255 (F8hex … FFhex) are reserved and must not be used.
[src:modbus-protocol/modbus] The master doesn't need to have an address.
[src:modbus-protocol/modbus] The communication process is initiated by the master, as only it can initiate a Modbus transaction.
[src:modbus-protocol/modbus] A slave will never transmit any data or perform any action without a request from the master, and slaves cannot communicate with each other.
[src:modbus-protocol/modbus] In Modbus over Serial Line, the master initiates requests to the slaves in *unicast* or *broadcast* modes.
[src:modbus-protocol/modbus] In *unicast mode*, the master will initiate a request to a single slave with a specific address.
[src:modbus-protocol/modbus] Upon receiving and finishing the request, the slave will respond with a message to the master.
[src:modbus-protocol/modbus] In this mode, a Modbus transaction includes two messages: one request from the master and one reply from the slave.
[src:modbus-protocol/modbus] Each slave must have a unique address (from 1 to 247) to be addressed independently for the communication.
[src:modbus-protocol/modbus] In *broadcast mode*, the master can send a request to all the slaves, using the broadcast address 0, which is the address reserved for broadcast exchanges (and not the master address).
[src:modbus-protocol/modbus] Slaves must accept broadcast exchanges but must not respond.
[src:modbus-protocol/modbus] The mapping of PDU of Modbus to the serial bus of Modbus over Serial Line protocol results in Modbus Serial Line PDU.
[src:modbus-protocol/modbus] On the physical layer, MODBUS over Serial Line performs its communication on bit by RS485 or RS232, with TIA/EIA-485 Two-Wire interface as the most popular way.
[src:modbus-protocol/modbus] TIA/EIA-232-E (RS232) can also be used but is limited to point-to-point short-range communication.
[src:modbus-protocol/modbus] MODBUS over Serial Line has two transmission modes *RTU* and *ASCII* which are corresponded to two versions of the protocol, known as *Modbus RTU* and *Modbus ASCII*.
[src:modbus-protocol/modbus] Modbus RTU (Remote Terminal Unit), which is the most common implementation available for Modbus, makes use of a compact, binary representation of the data for protocol communication.
[src:modbus-protocol/modbus] The RTU format follows the commands/data with a cyclic redundancy check checksum as an error check mechanism to ensure the reliability of data.
[src:modbus-protocol/modbus] A Modbus RTU message must be transmitted continuously without inter-character hesitations.
[src:modbus-protocol/modbus] Modbus messages are framed (separated) by idle (silent) periods.
[src:modbus-protocol/modbus] The default is even parity, while odd or no parity may be implemented as additional options.
[src:modbus-protocol/modbus] The CRC calculation is widely known as CRC-16-MODBUS, whose polynomial is *x*16 + *x*15 + *x*2 + 1 (normal hexadecimal algebraic polynomial being `8005` and reversed `A001`).
[src:modbus-protocol/modbus] Example of a Modbus RTU frame in hexadecimal: `01 04 02 FF FF B8 80` (CRC-16-MODBUS calculation for the 5 bytes from `01` to `FF` gives `80B8`, which is transmitted least significant byte first).
[src:modbus-protocol/modbus] To ensure frame integrity during the transmission, the time interval between two frames must be at least the transmission time of 3.5 characters, and the time interval between two consecutive characters must be no more than the transmission time of 1.5 characters.
[src:modbus-protocol/modbus] For higher data rates, Modbus RTU recommends to use the fixed values 750 μs for t1.5 and 1.750 ms for t3.5.
[src:modbus-protocol/modbus] Modbus ASCII makes use of ASCII characters (chars) for protocol communication.
[src:modbus-protocol/modbus] The ASCII format uses a longitudinal redundancy check checksum.
[src:modbus-protocol/modbus] Modbus ASCII messages are framed by a leading colon (":", ASCII value 3A16) and trailing newline (CR/LF, ASCII values 0D16 and 0A16).
[src:modbus-protocol/modbus] Modbus ASCII frame do not need to be sent in bursts like Modbus RTU, a delay up to 1 second is permitted between each character transmission by default.
[src:modbus-protocol/modbus] Address, Function, Data, and LRC are ASCII hexadecimal encoded values, whereby each byte (8 bits) of information is encoded as two human-readable ASCII characters from the ranges 0–9 and A–F.
[src:modbus-protocol/modbus] For example, a byte value of 122 (11110102 or 7A16) is encoded as two ASCII characters, "7" and "A", and transmitted as two bytes, `55` (3716, ASCII value for "7") and `65` (4116, ASCII value for "A").
[src:modbus-protocol/modbus] LRC is calculated as the sum of 8-bit values (excluding the start and end characters), negated (two's complement) and encoded as an 8-bit value.
[src:modbus-protocol/modbus] LRC is specified for use only as a checksum: because it is calculated on the encoded data rather than the transmitted characters, its 'longitudinal' characteristic is not available for use with parity bits to locate single-bit errors.
[src:modbus-protocol/modbus] Modbus TCP nomenclature is the same as for the Modbus over Serial line protocol, as any device which send out a Modbus command, is the 'client' and the response comes from a 'server'.
[src:modbus-protocol/modbus] The ADU for Modbus TCP is officially called *Modbus TCP/IP ADU* by the Modbus organization and is also called *Modbus TCP frame* by other parties.
[src:modbus-protocol/modbus] MODBUS Application Protocol header - is the dedicated header used on TCP/IP to identify the MODBUS Application Data Unit.
[src:modbus-protocol/modbus] Data models and function calls are identical for the first four variants listed above; only the encapsulation is different.
[src:modbus-protocol/modbus] However the variants are not interoperable, nor are the frame formats.
[src:modbus-protocol/modbus] Another *de facto* protocol closely related to Modbus appeared later, and was defined by PLC maker April Automates, the result of a collaborative effort between French companies Renault Automation and Merlin Gerin et Cie in 1985: JBUS.
[src:modbus-protocol/modbus] Differences between Modbus and JBUS at that time (number of entities, server stations) are now irrelevant as this protocol almost disappeared with the April PLC series, which AEG Schneider Automation bought in 1994 and then made obsolete.
[src:modbus-protocol/modbus] However, the name JBUS has survived to some extent.
[src:modbus-protocol/remote-terminal-unit] Other terms that may be used for RTU are **remote telemetry unit** and **remote telecontrol unit**.
[src:modbus-protocol/remote-terminal-unit] An RTU monitors the field digital and analog parameters and transmits data to a SCADA Master Station.
[src:modbus-protocol/remote-terminal-unit] It runs setup software to connect data input streams to data output streams, define communication protocols, and troubleshoot installation problems in the field.
[src:modbus-protocol/remote-terminal-unit] An RTU might even be a small process control unit with a small database for PID, Alarming, Filtering, Trending and other functions complemented with some BASIC (programming language) tasks.
[src:modbus-protocol/remote-terminal-unit] Modern RTUs typically support the IEC 61131-3 programming standard for programmable logic controllers.
[src:modbus-protocol/remote-terminal-unit] For example, it communicates via RS485 or wireless communication links in a multi-drop configuration.
[src:modbus-protocol/remote-terminal-unit] In this type of configuration it is a remote unit that collects data and performs simple control tasks.
[src:modbus-protocol/remote-terminal-unit] It does not have moving parts and uses extremely low power and is often solar powered.
[src:modbus-protocol/remote-terminal-unit] A form of power supply will be included for operation from the AC mains for various CPU, status wetting voltages and other interface cards.
[src:modbus-protocol/remote-terminal-unit] This may consist of AC to DC converters where operated from a station battery system.
[src:modbus-protocol/remote-terminal-unit] RTUs may include a battery and charger circuitry to continue operation in event of AC power failure for critical applications where a station battery is not available.
[src:modbus-protocol/remote-terminal-unit] Most RTUs have a section called *input status cards* to read ON/OFF information from the field.
[src:modbus-protocol/remote-terminal-unit] They do this by checking if a contact (like a switch) is open or closed at the RTU location.
[src:modbus-protocol/remote-terminal-unit] Some RTUs can also count events (like how many times a contact opens/closes), but this is optional.
[src:modbus-protocol/remote-terminal-unit] An RTU can monitor analog inputs of different types including 0-1 mA, 4–20 mA current loop, 0–10 V., ±2.5 V, ±5.0 V etc.
[src:modbus-protocol/remote-terminal-unit] Many RTU inputs buffer larger quantities via transducers to convert and isolate real-world quantities from sensitive RTU input levels.
[src:modbus-protocol/remote-terminal-unit] An RTU can also receive analog data via a communication system from a master or intelligent electronic device (IED) sending data values to it.
[src:modbus-protocol/remote-terminal-unit] The RTU or host system translates and scales this raw data into the appropriate units such as the quantity of water left, temperature degrees, or Megawatts, before presenting the data to the user via the human–machine interface.
[src:modbus-protocol/remote-terminal-unit] RTUs may drive high current capacity relays to a digital output (or "DO") board to switch power on and off to devices in the field.
[src:modbus-protocol/remote-terminal-unit] The DO board switches voltage to the coil in the relay, which closes the high current contacts, which completes the power circuit to the device.
[src:modbus-protocol/remote-terminal-unit] RTU outputs may also consist of driving a sensitive logic input on an electronic PLC, or other electronic device using a sensitive 5 V input.
[src:modbus-protocol/remote-terminal-unit] While not as commonly used, analog outputs may be included to control devices that require varying quantities, such as graphic recording instruments (strip charts).
[src:modbus-protocol/remote-terminal-unit] Summed or processed data quantities may be generated in a master SCADA system and output for display locally or remotely, wherever needed.
[src:modbus-protocol/remote-terminal-unit] Modern RTUs are usually capable of executing simple programs autonomously without involving the host computers of the DCS or SCADA system to simplify deployment and to provide redundancy for safety reasons.
[src:modbus-protocol/remote-terminal-unit] An RTU in a modern water management system will typically have code to modify its behavior when physical override switches on the RTU are toggled during maintenance-by-maintenance personnel.
[src:modbus-protocol/remote-terminal-unit] This is done for safety reasons; a miscommunication between the system operators and the maintenance personnel could cause system operators to mistakenly enable power to a water pump when it is being replaced, for example.
[src:modbus-protocol/remote-terminal-unit] Maintenance personnel should have any equipment they are working on disconnected from power and locked to prevent damage and/or injury.
[src:modbus-protocol/remote-terminal-unit] An RTU may be interfaced to multiple master stations and IEDs with different communication protocols (usually serial (RS-232, RS-485, RS-422) or Ethernet).
[src:modbus-protocol/remote-terminal-unit] An RTU may support standard protocols (Modbus, IEC 60870-5-101/103/104, DNP3, IEC 60870-6-ICCP, IEC 61850 etc.) to interface any third-party software.
[src:modbus-protocol/remote-terminal-unit] Data transfer may be initiated from either end using various techniques to ensure synchronization with minimal data traffic.
[src:modbus-protocol/remote-terminal-unit] The master may poll its subordinate unit (Master to RTU or RTU to IED) for changes of data on a periodic basis.
[src:modbus-protocol/remote-terminal-unit] Analog value changes will usually be reported only on changes outside a set limit from the last transmitted value.
[src:modbus-protocol/remote-terminal-unit] Digital (status) values observe a similar technique and only transmit groups (bytes) when one included point (bit) changes.
[src:modbus-protocol/remote-terminal-unit] Another method used is where a subordinate unit initiates an update of data upon a predetermined change in analog or digital data.
[src:modbus-protocol/remote-terminal-unit] Complete data transmission must be performed periodically, with either method, to ensure full synchronization and eliminate stale data.
[src:modbus-protocol/remote-terminal-unit] Most communication protocols support both methods, programmable by the installer.
[src:modbus-protocol/remote-terminal-unit] Multiple RTUs or IEDs may share a communications line, in a multi-drop scheme, as units are addressed uniquely and only respond to their own polls and commands.
[src:modbus-protocol/remote-terminal-unit] IED communications transfer data between the RTU and an IED.
[src:modbus-protocol/remote-terminal-unit] This can eliminate the need for many hardware status inputs, analog inputs, and relay outputs in the RTU.
[src:modbus-protocol/remote-terminal-unit] Communications are accomplished by copper or fibre optics lines.
[src:modbus-protocol/remote-terminal-unit] Master communications usually occur between an RTU and a larger control system or a data collection system (incorporated into a larger system).
[src:modbus-protocol/remote-terminal-unit] Data may be moved using a copper, fibre optic or radio frequency communication system.
[src:modbus-protocol/rs-485] RS-485 supports inexpensive local networks and multidrop communications links, using the same differential signaling over twisted pair as RS-422.
[src:modbus-protocol/rs-485] It is generally accepted that RS-485 can be used with data rates up to 10 Mbit/s or, at lower speeds, distances up to 1,200 m (4,000 ft).
[src:modbus-protocol/rs-485] As a rule of thumb, the speed in bit/s multiplied by the length in meters should not exceed 108.
[src:modbus-protocol/rs-485] Thus a 50-meter cable should not signal faster than 2 Mbit/s.
[src:modbus-protocol/rs-485] In contrast to RS-422, which has a driver circuit which cannot be switched off, RS-485 drivers use three-state logic allowing individual transmitters to be deactivated.
[src:modbus-protocol/rs-485] This allows RS-485 to implement linear bus topologies using only two wires.
[src:modbus-protocol/rs-485] The equipment located along a set of RS-485 wires are interchangeably called nodes, stations or devices.
[src:modbus-protocol/rs-485] The recommended arrangement of the wires is as a connected series of point-to-point (multidropped) nodes, i.e. a line or bus, not a star, ring, or multiply connected network.
[src:modbus-protocol/rs-485] Star and ring topologies are not recommended because of signal reflections or excessively low or high termination impedance.
[src:modbus-protocol/rs-485] If a star configuration is unavoidable, special RS-485 repeaters are available which bidirectionally listen for data on each span and then retransmit the data onto all other spans.
[src:modbus-protocol/rs-485] Ideally, the two ends of the cable will have a termination resistor connected across the two wires.
[src:modbus-protocol/rs-485] Without termination resistors, signal reflections off the unterminated end of the cable can cause data corruption.
[src:modbus-protocol/rs-485] Termination resistors also reduce electrical noise sensitivity due to the lower impedance.
[src:modbus-protocol/rs-485] The value of each termination resistor should be equal to the cable characteristic impedance (typically, 120 ohms for twisted pairs).
[src:modbus-protocol/rs-485] The termination also includes pull up and pull down resistors to establish bias for each data wire for the case when the lines are not being driven by any device.
[src:modbus-protocol/rs-485] This way, the lines will be biased to known voltages and nodes will not interpret the noise from undriven lines as actual data; without biasing resistors, the data lines float in such a way that electrical noise sensitivity is greatest when all device stations are silent or unpowered.
[src:modbus-protocol/rs-485] The EIA once labeled all its standards with the prefix RS (Recommended Standard), but the EIA/TIA officially replaced RS with EIA/TIA to help identify the origin of its standards.
[src:modbus-protocol/rs-485] The EIA has officially disbanded and the standard is now maintained by the TIA as TIA-485, but engineers and applications guides continue to use the RS-485 designation.
[src:modbus-protocol/rs-485] The initial edition of EIA RS-485 was dated April 1983.
[src:modbus-protocol/rs-485] RS-485 only specifies the electrical characteristics of the generator and the receiver: the physical layer.
[src:modbus-protocol/rs-485] It does not specify or recommend any communications protocol; Other standards define the protocols for communication over an RS-485 link.
[src:modbus-protocol/rs-485] The foreword to the standard references *The Telecommunications Systems Bulletin TSB-89* which contains application guidelines, including data signaling rate vs. cable length, stub length, and configurations.
[src:modbus-protocol/rs-485] Section 4 defines the electrical characteristics of the generator (transmitter or driver), receiver, transceiver, and system.
[src:modbus-protocol/rs-485] These characteristics include: definition of a unit load, voltage ranges, open-circuit voltages, thresholds, and transient tolerance.
[src:modbus-protocol/rs-485] It also defines three generator interface points (signal lines); A, B and C.
[src:modbus-protocol/rs-485] This section also defines the logic states 1 (off) and 0 (on), by the polarity between A and B terminals.
[src:modbus-protocol/rs-485] If A is negative with respect to B, the state is binary 1.
[src:modbus-protocol/rs-485] The reversed polarity (A positive with respect to B) is binary 0.
[src:modbus-protocol/rs-485] The standard does not assign any logic function to the two states.
[src:modbus-protocol/rs-485] RS-485, like RS-422, can be made full-duplex by using four wires.
[src:modbus-protocol/rs-485] Since RS-485 is a multi-point specification, however, this is not necessary or desirable in many cases.
[src:modbus-protocol/rs-485] RS-485 and RS-422 can interoperate with certain restrictions.
[src:modbus-protocol/rs-485] Converters between RS-485 and RS-232 are available to allow a personal computer to communicate with remote devices.
[src:modbus-protocol/rs-485] By using repeaters very large RS-485 networks can be formed.
[src:modbus-protocol/rs-485] TSB-89A, Application Guidelines for TIA/EIA-485-A does not recommend using star topology, as doing so may lead to long stubs (branches of the star), which can cause signal reflections that make data transmission unreliable.
[src:modbus-protocol/rs-485] RS-485 does not define a communication protocol; merely an electrical interface.
[src:modbus-protocol/rs-485] Although many applications use RS-485 signal levels, the speed, format, and protocol of the data transmission are not specified by RS-485.
[src:modbus-protocol/rs-485] Interoperability of even similar devices from different manufacturers is not assured by compliance with the signal levels alone.
[src:modbus-protocol/rs-485] RS-485 signals are used in a wide range of computer and automation systems.
[src:modbus-protocol/rs-485] In a computer system, SCSI-2 and SCSI-3 may use RS-485 to implement the physical layer for data transmission between a controller and a disk drive.
[src:modbus-protocol/rs-485] RS-485 is used for low-speed data communications in commercial aircraft cabins' vehicle bus.
[src:modbus-protocol/rs-485] It requires minimal wiring and can share the wiring among several seats, reducing weight.
[src:modbus-protocol/rs-485] These are used in programmable logic controllers and on factory floors.
[src:modbus-protocol/rs-485] RS-485 is used as the physical layer underlying many standard and proprietary automation protocols used to implement industrial control systems, including the most common versions of Modbus and Profibus.
[src:modbus-protocol/rs-485] **DH 485** is a proprietary communications protocol used by Allen-Bradley in their line of industrial control units.
[src:modbus-protocol/rs-485] Utilizing a series of dedicated interface devices, it allows PCs and industrial controllers to communicate.
[src:modbus-protocol/rs-485] Since it is differential, it resists electromagnetic interference from motors and welding equipment.
[src:modbus-protocol/rs-485] In theatre and performance venues, RS-485 networks are used to control lighting and other systems using the DMX512 protocol.
[src:modbus-protocol/rs-485] RS-485 serves as a physical layer for the AES3 digital audio interconnect.
[src:modbus-protocol/rs-485] RS-485 is also used in building automation as the simple bus wiring and long cable length is ideal for joining remote devices.
[src:modbus-protocol/rs-485] It may be used to control video surveillance systems or to interconnect security control panels and devices such as access control card readers.
[src:modbus-protocol/rs-485] It is also used in Digital Command Control (DCC) for model railways.
[src:modbus-protocol/rs-485] The external interface to the DCC command station is often RS-485 used by hand-held controllers or for controlling the layout in a networked PC environment.
[src:modbus-protocol/rs-485] 8P8C modular connectors are used in this case.
[src:modbus-protocol/rs-485] Because a mark (logic 1) condition is traditionally represented (e.g. in RS-232) with a negative voltage; and space (logic 0) represented with a positive one, A may be considered the *non-inverting* signal and B as inverting.
[src:modbus-protocol/rs-485] The truth tables of most popular devices, starting with the SN75176, show the output signals inverted.
[src:modbus-protocol/rs-485] These manufacturers all agree on the meaning of the standard, and their practice is in widespread use.
[src:modbus-protocol/rs-485] The issue also exists in programmable logic controller applications.
[src:modbus-protocol/rs-485] Care must be taken when using A/B naming.
[src:modbus-protocol/rs-485] RS-485 standard conformant drivers provide a differential output of a minimum 1.5 V across a 54-Ω load, whereas standard conformant receivers detect a differential input down to 200 mV.
[src:modbus-protocol/rs-485] The two values provide a sufficient margin for a reliable data transmission even under severe signal degradation across the cable and connectors.
[src:modbus-protocol/rs-485] This robustness is the main reason why RS-485 is well suited for long-distance networking in noisy environment.
[src:modbus-protocol/rs-485] This connection may be used to limit the common-mode signal that can be impressed on the receiver inputs.
[src:modbus-protocol/rs-485] The allowable common-mode voltage is in the range −7 V to +12 V, i.e. ±7 V on top of the 0–5 V signal range.
[src:modbus-protocol/rs-485] Failure to stay within this range will result in, at best, signal corruption, and, at worst, damage to connected devices.
[src:modbus-protocol/rs-485] Care must be taken that an SC connection, especially over long cable runs, does not result in an attempt to connect disparate grounds together – it is wise to add some current limiting to the SC connection.
[src:modbus-protocol/rs-485] Grounds between buildings may vary by a small voltage, but with very low impedance and hence the possibility of catastrophic currents – enough to melt signal cables, PCB traces, and transceiver devices.
[src:modbus-protocol/rs-485] RS-485 does not specify any connector or pinout.
[src:modbus-protocol/rs-485] Circuits may be terminated on screw terminals, D-subminiature connectors, or other types of connectors.
[src:modbus-protocol/rs-485] The standard does not discuss cable shielding but makes some recommendations on preferred methods of interconnecting the signal reference common and equipment case grounds.
[src:modbus-protocol/rs-485] The diagram below shows potentials of the A (blue) and B (red) pins of an RS-485 line before, during, and after transmission of one byte (0xD3, least significant bit first) of data using an asynchronous start-stop method.
[src:modbus-protocol/scada] The operator interfaces, which enable monitoring and the issuing of process commands, such as controller setpoint changes, are handled through the SCADA computer system.
[src:modbus-protocol/scada] The subordinated operations, e.g. the real-time control logic or controller calculations, are performed by networked modules connected to the field sensors and actuators.
[src:modbus-protocol/scada] The SCADA concept was developed to be a universal means of remote-access to a variety of local control modules, which could be from different manufacturers and allowing access through standard automation protocols.
[src:modbus-protocol/scada] In practice, large SCADA systems have grown to become similar to DCSs in function, while using multiple means of interfacing with the plant.
[src:modbus-protocol/scada] They can control large-scale processes spanning multiple sites, and work over large distances.
[src:modbus-protocol/scada] It is one of the most commonly used types of industrial control systems.
[src:modbus-protocol/scada] The key attribute of a SCADA system is its ability to perform a supervisory operation over a variety of other proprietary devices.
[src:modbus-protocol/scada] Level 1 contains the programmable logic controllers (PLCs) or remote terminal units (RTUs).
[src:modbus-protocol/scada] Level 2 contains the SCADA to readings and equipment status reports that are communicated to level 2 SCADA as required.
[src:modbus-protocol/scada] Data is then compiled and formatted in such a way that a control room operator using the human-machine interface (HMI) can make supervisory decisions to adjust or override normal RTU (PLC) controls.
[src:modbus-protocol/scada] Data may also be fed to a historian, often built on a commodity database management system, to allow trending and other analytical auditing.
[src:modbus-protocol/scada] SCADA systems typically use a *tag database*, which contains data elements called *tags* or *points*, which relate to specific instrumentation or actuators within the process system.
[src:modbus-protocol/scada] Data is accumulated against these unique process control equipment tag references.
[src:modbus-protocol/scada] This is the core of the SCADA system, gathering data on the process and sending control commands to the field connected devices.
[src:modbus-protocol/scada] It refers to the computer and software responsible for communicating with the field connection controllers, which are RTUs and PLCs, and includes the HMI software running on operator workstations.
[src:modbus-protocol/scada] In smaller SCADA systems, the supervisory computer may be composed of a single PC, in which case the HMI is a part of this computer.
[src:modbus-protocol/scada] In larger SCADA systems, the master station may include several HMIs hosted on client computers, multiple servers for data acquisition, distributed software applications, and disaster recovery sites.
[src:modbus-protocol/scada] formation providing continuous control and monitoring in the event of a server malfunction or breakdown.
[src:modbus-protocol/scada] connect to sensors and actuators in the process, and are networked to the supervisory computer system.
[src:modbus-protocol/scada] system, using radio, GSM or satellite for communications, and being ruggedised to survive from -20C to +70C or even -40C to +85C without external heating or cooling equipment.
[src:modbus-protocol/scada] PLCs are connected to sensors and actuators in the process, and are networked to the supervisory system.
[src:modbus-protocol/scada] In factory automation, PLCs typically have a high speed connection to the SCADA system.
[src:modbus-protocol/scada] In remote applications, such as a large water treatment plant, PLCs may connect directly to SCADA over a wireless link, or more commonly, utilise an RTU for the communications management.
[src:modbus-protocol/scada] For economical reasons, PLCs are often used for remote sites where there is a large I/O count, rather than utilising an RTU alone.
[src:modbus-protocol/scada] This connects the supervisory computer system to the RTUs and PLCs, and may use industry standard or manufacturer proprietary protocols.
[src:modbus-protocol/scada] Both RTUs and PLCs operate autonomously on the near-real time control of the process, using the last command given from the supervisory system.
[src:modbus-protocol/scada] Failure of the communications network does not necessarily stop the plant process controls, and on resumption of communications, the operator can continue with monitoring and control.
[src:modbus-protocol/scada] Some critical systems will have dual redundant data highways, often cabled via diverse routes.
[src:modbus-protocol/scada] The HMI is the operator window of the supervisory system.
[src:modbus-protocol/scada] It presents plant information to the operating personnel graphically in the form of mimic diagrams, which are a schematic representation of the plant being controlled, and alarm and event logging pages.
[src:modbus-protocol/scada] The HMI is linked to the SCADA supervisory computer to provide live data to drive the mimic diagrams, alarm displays and trending graphs.
[src:modbus-protocol/scada] In many installations the HMI is the graphical user interface for the operator, collects all data from external devices, creates reports, performs alarming, sends notifications, etc.
[src:modbus-protocol/scada] Mimic diagrams consist of line graphics and schematic symbols to represent process elements, or may consist of digital photographs of the process equipment overlain with animated symbols.
[src:modbus-protocol/scada] Supervisory operation of the plant is by means of the HMI, with operators issuing commands using mouse pointers, keyboards and touch screens.
[src:modbus-protocol/scada] For example, a symbol of a pump can show the operator that the pump is running, and a flow meter symbol can show how much fluid it is pumping through the pipe.
[src:modbus-protocol/scada] The operator can switch the pump off from the mimic by a mouse click or screen touch.
[src:modbus-protocol/scada] The HMI will show the flow rate of the fluid in the pipe decrease in real time.
[src:modbus-protocol/scada] The HMI package for a SCADA system typically includes a drawing program that the operators or system maintenance personnel use to change the way these points are represented in the interface.
[src:modbus-protocol/scada] These representations can be as simple as an on-screen traffic light, which represents the state of an actual traffic light in the field, or as complex as a multi-projector display representing the position of all of the elevators in a skyscraper or all of the trains on a railway.
[src:modbus-protocol/scada] is a software service within the HMI which accumulates time-stamped data, events, and alarms in a database which can be queried or used to populate graphic trends in the HMI.
[src:modbus-protocol/scada] The historian is a client that requests data from a data acquisition server.
[src:modbus-protocol/scada] An important part of most SCADA implementations is alarm handling.
[src:modbus-protocol/scada] The system monitors whether certain alarm conditions are satisfied, to determine when an alarm event has occurred.
[src:modbus-protocol/scada] Once an alarm event has been detected, one or more actions are taken (such as the activation of one or more alarm indicators, and perhaps the generation of email or text messages so that management or remote SCADA operators are informed).
[src:modbus-protocol/scada] In many cases, a SCADA operator may have to acknowledge the alarm event; this may deactivate some alarm indicators, whereas other indicators remain active until the alarm conditions are cleared.
[src:modbus-protocol/scada] "Smart" RTUs, or standard PLCs, are capable of autonomously executing simple logic processes without involving the supervisory computer.
[src:modbus-protocol/scada] Unlike a procedural language like C or FORTRAN, IEC 61131-3 has minimal training requirements by virtue of resembling historic physical control arrays.
[src:modbus-protocol/scada] This allows SCADA system engineers to perform both the design and implementation of a program to be executed on an RTU or PLC.
[src:modbus-protocol/scada] A programmable automation controller (PAC) is a compact controller that combines the features and capabilities of a PC-based control system with that of a typical PLC.
[src:modbus-protocol/scada] PACs are deployed in SCADA systems to provide RTU and PLC functions.
[src:modbus-protocol/scada] In many electrical substation SCADA applications, "distributed RTUs" use information processors or station computers to communicate with digital protective relays, PACs, and other devices for I/O, and communicate with the SCADA master in lieu of a traditional RTU.
[src:modbus-protocol/scada] Since about 1998, virtually all major PLC manufacturers have offered integrated HMI/SCADA systems, many of them using open and non-proprietary communications protocols.
[src:modbus-protocol/scada] The Remote Terminal Unit (RTU) connects to physical equipment.
[src:modbus-protocol/scada] Typically, an RTU converts the electrical signals from the equipment to digital values.
[src:modbus-protocol/scada] By converting and sending these electrical signals out to equipment the RTU can control equipment.
[src:modbus-protocol/scada] SCADA systems have traditionally used combinations of radio and direct wired connections, although SONET/SDH is also frequently used for large systems such as railways and power stations.
[src:modbus-protocol/scada] The remote management or monitoring function of a SCADA system is often referred to as telemetry.
[src:modbus-protocol/scada] Some users want SCADA data to travel over their pre-established corporate networks or to share the network with other applications.
[src:modbus-protocol/scada] The legacy of the early low-bandwidth protocols remains, though.
[src:modbus-protocol/scada] SCADA protocols are designed to be very compact.
[src:modbus-protocol/scada] Many are designed to send information only when the master station polls the RTU.
[src:modbus-protocol/scada] Typical legacy SCADA protocols include Modbus RTU, RP-570, Profibus and Conitel.
[src:modbus-protocol/scada] These communication protocols, with the exception of Modbus (Modbus has been made open by Schneider Electric), are all SCADA-vendor specific but are widely adopted and used.
[src:modbus-protocol/scada] These communication protocols are standardized and recognized by all major SCADA vendors.
[src:modbus-protocol/scada] Many of these protocols now contain extensions to operate over TCP/IP.
[src:modbus-protocol/scada] Although the use of conventional networking specifications, such as TCP/IP, blurs the line between traditional and industrial networking, they each fulfill fundamentally differing requirements.
[src:modbus-protocol/scada] Network simulation can be used in conjunction with SCADA simulators to perform various 'what-if' analyses.
[src:modbus-protocol/scada] With increasing security demands (such as North American Electric Reliability Corporation (NERC) and critical infrastructure protection (CIP) in the US), there is increasing use of satellite-based communication.
[src:modbus-protocol/scada] This has the key advantages that the infrastructure can be self-contained (not using circuits from the public telephone system), can have built-in encryption, and can be engineered to the availability and reliability required by the SCADA system operator.
[src:modbus-protocol/scada] Earlier experiences using consumer-grade VSAT were poor.
[src:modbus-protocol/scada] Modern carrier-class systems provide the quality of service required for SCADA.
[src:modbus-protocol/scada] RTUs and other automatic controller devices were developed before the advent of industry wide standards for interoperability.
[src:modbus-protocol/scada] The result is that developers and their management created a multitude of control protocols.
[src:modbus-protocol/scada] Among the larger vendors, there was also the incentive to create their own protocol to "lock in" their customer base.
[src:modbus-protocol/scada] A list of automation protocols is compiled here.
[src:modbus-protocol/scada] An example of efforts by vendor groups to standardize automation protocols is the OPC-UA (formerly "OLE for process control" now Open Platform Communications Unified Architecture).
[src:modbus-protocol/scada] Early SCADA system computing was done by large minicomputers.
[src:modbus-protocol/scada] Common network services did not exist at the time SCADA was developed.
[src:modbus-protocol/scada] Thus SCADA systems were independent systems with no connectivity to other systems.
[src:modbus-protocol/scada] The communication protocols used were strictly proprietary at that time.
[src:modbus-protocol/scada] The first-generation SCADA system redundancy was achieved using a back-up mainframe system connected to all the remote terminal unit sites and was used in the event of failure of the primary mainframe system.
[src:modbus-protocol/scada] Some first generation SCADA systems were developed as "turn key" operations that ran on minicomputers such as the PDP-11 series.
[src:modbus-protocol/scada] SCADA information and command processing were distributed across multiple stations which were connected through a LAN.
[src:modbus-protocol/scada] Information was shared in near real time.
[src:modbus-protocol/scada] Each station was responsible for a particular task, which reduced the cost as compared to first generation SCADA.
[src:modbus-protocol/scada] The network protocols used were still not standardized.
[src:modbus-protocol/scada] Since these protocols were proprietary, very few people beyond the developers knew enough to determine how secure a SCADA installation was.
[src:modbus-protocol/scada] Security of the SCADA installation was usually overlooked.
[src:modbus-protocol/scada] Similar to a distributed architecture, any complex SCADA can be reduced to the simplest components and connected through communication protocols.
[src:modbus-protocol/scada] In the case of a networked design, the system may be spread across more than one LAN network called a process control network (PCN) and separated geographically.
[src:modbus-protocol/scada] Several distributed architecture SCADAs running in parallel, with a single supervisor and historian, could be considered a network architecture.
[src:modbus-protocol/scada] This allows for a more cost-effective solution in very large scale systems.
[src:modbus-protocol/scada] The growth of the internet has led SCADA systems to implement web technologies allowing users to view data, exchange information and control processes from anywhere in the world through standard web protocols such as HTTPS and WebSocket for live updates.
[src:modbus-protocol/scada] The early 2000s saw the proliferation of Web SCADA systems.
[src:modbus-protocol/scada] Web SCADA systems use web browsers such as Google Chrome and Mozilla Firefox as the graphical user interface (GUI) for the operators HMI.
[src:modbus-protocol/scada] This simplifies the client side installation and enables users to access the system from various platforms with web browsers such as servers, personal computers, laptops, tablets and mobile phones.
[src:modbus-protocol/scada] SCADA systems that tie together decentralized facilities such as power, oil, gas pipelines, water distribution and wastewater collection systems were designed to be open, robust, and easily operated and repaired, but not necessarily secure.
[src:modbus-protocol/scada] The move from proprietary technologies to more standardized and open solutions together with the increased number of connections between SCADA systems, office networks and the Internet has made them more vulnerable to types of network attacks that are relatively common in computer security.
[src:modbus-protocol/scada] Security researcher Jerry Brown submitted a similar advisory regarding a buffer overflow vulnerability in a Wonderware InBatchClient ActiveX control.
[src:modbus-protocol/scada] Both vendors made updates available prior to public vulnerability release.
[src:modbus-protocol/scada] Mitigation recommendations were standard patching practices and requiring VPN access for secure connectivity.
[src:modbus-protocol/scada] Consequently, the security of some SCADA-based systems has come into question as they are seen as potentially vulnerable to cyber attacks.
[src:modbus-protocol/scada] SCADA systems are used to control and monitor physical processes, examples of which are transmission of electricity, transportation of gas and oil in pipelines, water distribution, traffic lights, and other systems used as the basis of modern society.
[src:modbus-protocol/scada] The security of these SCADA systems is important because compromise or destruction of these systems would impact multiple areas of society far removed from the original compromise.
[src:modbus-protocol/scada] For example, a blackout caused by a compromised electrical SCADA system would cause financial losses to all the customers that received electricity from that source.
[src:modbus-protocol/scada] Legacy SCADA deployments can remain difficult to secure because control equipment is often geographically distributed, long-lived, and costly to replace or patch.
[src:modbus-protocol/scada] There are many threat vectors to a modern SCADA system.
[src:modbus-protocol/scada] One is the threat of unauthorized access to the control software, whether it is human access or changes induced intentionally or accidentally by virus infections and other software threats residing on the control host machine.
[src:modbus-protocol/scada] Another is the threat of packet access to the network segments hosting SCADA devices.
[src:modbus-protocol/scada] In many cases, the control protocol lacks any form of cryptographic security, allowing an attacker to control a SCADA device by sending commands over a network.
[src:modbus-protocol/scada] In many cases SCADA users have assumed that having a VPN offered sufficient protection, unaware that security can be trivially bypassed with physical access to SCADA-related network jacks and switches.
[src:modbus-protocol/scada] Industrial control vendors suggest approaching SCADA security like Information Security with a defense in depth strategy that leverages common IT practices.
[src:modbus-protocol/scada] Apart from that, research has shown that the architecture of SCADA systems has several other vulnerabilities, including direct tampering with RTUs, communication links from RTUs to the control center, and IT software and databases in the control center.
[src:modbus-protocol/scada] The RTUs could, for instance, be targets of deception attacks injecting false data or denial-of-service attacks.
[src:modbus-protocol/scada] The reliable function of SCADA systems in our modern infrastructure may be crucial to public health and safety.
[src:modbus-protocol/scada] As such, attacks on these systems may directly or indirectly threaten public health and safety.
[src:modbus-protocol/scada] Such an attack has already occurred, carried out on Maroochy Shire Council's sewage control system in Queensland, Australia.
[src:modbus-protocol/scada] Shortly after a contractor installed a SCADA system in January 2000, system components began to function erratically.
[src:modbus-protocol/scada] Pumps did not run when needed and alarms were not reported.
[src:modbus-protocol/scada] More critically, sewage flooded a nearby park and contaminated an open surface-water drainage ditch and flowed 500 meters to a tidal canal.
[src:modbus-protocol/scada] The SCADA system was directing sewage valves to open when the design protocol should have kept them closed.
[src:modbus-protocol/scada] Initially this was believed to be a system bug.
[src:modbus-protocol/scada] Monitoring of the system logs revealed the malfunctions were the result of cyber attacks.
[src:modbus-protocol/scada] Investigators reported 46 separate instances of malicious outside interference before the culprit was identified.
[src:modbus-protocol/scada] The attacks were made by a disgruntled ex-employee of the company that had installed the SCADA system.
[src:modbus-protocol/scada] The ex-employee was hoping to be hired by the utility full-time to maintain the system.
[src:modbus-protocol/scada] In April 2008, the *Commission to Assess the Threat to the United States from Electromagnetic Pulse (EMP) Attack* issued a *Critical Infrastructures Report* document which discussed the extreme vulnerability of SCADA systems to an electromagnetic pulse (EMP) event.
[src:modbus-protocol/scada] After testing and analysis, the commission concluded: "SCADA systems are vulnerable to EMP insult.
[src:modbus-protocol/scada] The large numbers and widespread reliance on such systems by all of the Nation’s critical infrastructures represent a systemic threat to their continued operation following an EMP event.
[src:modbus-protocol/scada] Many vendors of SCADA and control products have begun to address the risks posed by unauthorized access by developing lines of specialized industrial firewall and VPN solutions for TCP/IP-based SCADA networks as well as external SCADA monitoring and recording equipment.
[src:modbus-protocol/scada] The International Society of Automation (ISA) started formalizing SCADA security requirements in 2007 with a working group, WG4.
[src:modbus-protocol/scada] WG4 "deals specifically with unique technical requirements, measurements, and other features required to evaluate and assure security resilience and performance of industrial automation and control systems devices".
[src:modbus-protocol/scada] The increased interest in SCADA vulnerabilities has resulted in vulnerability researchers discovering vulnerabilities in commercial SCADA software and more general offensive SCADA techniques presented to the general security community.
[src:modbus-protocol/scada] In June 2010, anti-virus security company VirusBlokAda reported the first detection of malware that attacks SCADA systems (Siemens' WinCC/PCS 7 systems) running on Windows operating systems.
[src:modbus-protocol/scada] The malware is called Stuxnet and uses four zero-day attacks to install a rootkit which in turn logs into the SCADA's database and steals design and control files.
[src:modbus-protocol/scada] The malware is also capable of changing the control system and hiding those changes.
[src:modbus-protocol/scada] The malware was found on 14 systems, the majority of which were located in Iran.
[src:modbus-protocol/scada] In October 2013 *National Geographic* released a docudrama titled *American Blackout* which dealt with an imagined large-scale cyber attack on SCADA and the United States' electrical grid.
[src:modbus-protocol/scada] Both large and small systems can be built using the SCADA concept.
[src:modbus-protocol/scada] These systems can range from just tens to thousands of control loops, depending on the application.
[src:modbus-protocol/scada] However, SCADA systems may have security vulnerabilities, so the systems should be evaluated to identify risks and solutions implemented to mitigate those risks.
[src:modbus-protocol/serial-communication] In telecommunication and data transmission, **serial communication** is the process of sending data one bit at a time, sequentially, over a communication channel or computer bus.
[src:modbus-protocol/serial-communication] This is in contrast to parallel communication, where several bits are sent as a whole, on a link with several parallel channels.
[src:modbus-protocol/serial-communication] Serial communication is used for all long-haul communication and most computer networks, where the cost of cable and difficulty of synchronization make parallel communication impractical.
[src:modbus-protocol/serial-communication] The migration from PCI to PCI Express (PCIe) is an example.
[src:modbus-protocol/serial-communication] Modern high speed serial interfaces such as PCIe send data several bits at a time using modulation/encoding techniques such as PAM4 which groups 2 bits at a time into a single symbol, and several symbols are still sent one at a time.
[src:modbus-protocol/serial-communication] This replaces PAM2 or non return to zero (NRZ) which only sends one bit at a time, or in other words one bit per symbol.
[src:modbus-protocol/serial-communication] The symbols are sent at a speed known as the symbol rate or the baud rate.
[src:modbus-protocol/serial-communication] Many serial communication systems were originally designed to transfer data over relatively large distances through some sort of data cable.
[src:modbus-protocol/serial-communication] Practically all long-distance communication transmits data one bit at a time, rather than in parallel, because it reduces the cost of the cable.
[src:modbus-protocol/serial-communication] The cables that carry this data (other than "the" serial cable) and the computer ports they plug into are usually referred to with a more specific name, to reduce confusion.
[src:modbus-protocol/serial-communication] Keyboard and mouse cables and ports are almost invariably serial—such as PS/2 port, Apple Desktop Bus and USB.
[src:modbus-protocol/serial-communication] The cables that carry digital video are also mostly serial—such as coax cable plugged into a HD-SDI port, a webcam plugged into a USB port or FireWire port, Ethernet cable connecting an IP camera to a Power over Ethernet port, FPD-Link, digital telephone lines (ex.
[src:modbus-protocol/serial-communication] Other such cables and ports, transmitting data one bit at a time, include Serial ATA, Serial SCSI, Ethernet cable plugged into Ethernet ports, the Display Data Channel using previously reserved pins of the VGA connector or the DVI port or the HDMI port.
[src:modbus-protocol/serial-communication] Many communication systems were generally designed to connect two integrated circuits on the same printed circuit board, connected by signal traces on that board (rather than external cables).
[src:modbus-protocol/serial-communication] Integrated circuits are more expensive when they have more pins.
[src:modbus-protocol/serial-communication] To reduce the number of pins in a package, many ICs use a serial bus to transfer data when speed is not important.
[src:modbus-protocol/serial-communication] Some examples of such low-cost lower-speed serial buses include RS-232, DALI, SPI, CAN bus, I²C, UNI/O, and 1-Wire.
[src:modbus-protocol/serial-communication] Higher-speed serial buses include USB, SATA and PCI Express.
[src:modbus-protocol/serial-communication] The communication links, across which computers (or parts of computers) talk to one another, may be either serial or parallel.
[src:modbus-protocol/serial-communication] A parallel link transmits several streams of data simultaneously along multiple channels (e.g., wires, printed circuit tracks, or optical fibers); whereas, a serial link transmits only a single stream of data.
[src:modbus-protocol/serial-communication] The rationale for parallel communication was the added benefit of having Direct Memory Access to the 8-bit or 16-bit registry addresses at a time when mapping direct data lanes was more convenient and faster than synchronizing data serially.
[src:modbus-protocol/serial-communication] Although a serial link may seem inferior to a parallel one, since it can transmit less data per clock cycle, it is often the case that serial links can be clocked considerably faster than parallel links in order to achieve a higher data rate.
[src:modbus-protocol/serial-communication] The transition from parallel to serial buses was allowed by Moore's law which allowed for the incorporation of SerDes in integrated circuits.
[src:modbus-protocol/serial-communication] An electrical serial link only requires a pair of wires, whereas a parallel link requires several.
[src:modbus-protocol/serial-communication] Thus serial links can save on costs (also known as the Bill of Materials).
[src:modbus-protocol/serial-communication] Differential signalling uses length-matched wires or conductors and are used in high speed serial links.
[src:modbus-protocol/serial-communication] Length-matching is easier to perform on serial links as they require fewer conductors.
[src:modbus-protocol/serial-communication] In many cases, serial is cheaper to implement than parallel.
[src:modbus-protocol/serial-communication] Many ICs have serial interfaces, as opposed to parallel ones, so that they have fewer pins and are therefore less expensive.
[src:modbus-protocol/slave-technology] In engineering, **master–slave** is a relationship between two systems in which one controls the other.
[src:modbus-protocol/slave-technology] In some cases, one master controls just one slave system, but in others, there are multiple slave systems controlled by the same master.
[src:modbus-protocol/slave-technology] Sometimes the master is a different kind of system than the slave, but sometimes there are multiple similar systems and one of them is designated the master in order to centralize external (i.e., user) control of the collection.
[src:modbus-protocol/slave-technology] Due to it being prone to being associated with slavery, the terminology is a subject of controversy and has been replaced with alternative terms in some cases.
[src:modbus-protocol/slave-technology] In photography, secondary, or slave, flash units are connected to a master unit to provide synchronized lighting.
[src:modbus-protocol/slave-technology] Parallel audio duplication often entails multiple recording with devices (i.e., for cassette tape or compact disc) linked together so that operating the controls of a master device triggers the same commands on slave devices.
[src:modbus-protocol/slave-technology] Railway locomotives operating in the same train (for example, to pull a load too heavy for a single locomotive) may be configured for master–slave operation with all but one of the locomotives controlled from the first.
[src:modbus-protocol/slave-technology] In a hydraulic system, a master cylinder is a control device that converts force into hydraulic pressure that drives movement in a slave cylinder at the other end of the hydraulic line.
[src:modbus-protocol/slave-technology] A common application is a vehicle brake system.
[src:modbus-protocol/slave-technology] A master clock provides time signals used to synchronize one or more slave clocks as part of a clock network.
[src:modbus-protocol/slave-technology] A slave clock receives and displays the time from a master, though it may be able to keep time itself if the master is not working.
[src:modbus-protocol/slave-technology] Computer bus protocols often use a master-slave relationship.
[src:modbus-protocol/slave-technology] For instance, a USB host manages access to the USB bus shared by any number of USB devices.
[src:modbus-protocol/slave-technology] A serial peripheral interface (SPI) bus typically has a single master controlling multiple slaves.
[src:modbus-protocol/slave-technology] I2C and I3C may even have multiple masters on a bus.
[src:modbus-protocol/slave-technology] Modbus also uses a master device to initiate connection requests to slave devices.
[src:modbus-protocol/slave-technology] An edge-triggered flip-flop can be created by arranging two gated latches in a master–slave configuration.
[src:modbus-protocol/slave-technology] It is so named because the master latch controls the slave latch's value and forces the slave latch to hold its value, as the slave latch always copies its new value from the master latch.
[src:modbus-protocol/slave-technology] In database replication, the master database is the authoritative source.
[src:modbus-protocol/slave-technology] The slave or replica database is controlled by the master database, which repeats its update commands (for example by way of event log) to the slave.
[src:modbus-protocol/slave-technology] Some databases implement so called *multi-master replication*, where a mix of writeable master nodes and readable nodes is used.
[src:modbus-protocol/slave-technology] These databases are used in scenarios where performance is an acceptable tradeoff for ACID properties, for example, non-mission-critical data, like suggesting similar purchases.
[src:modbus-protocol/slave-technology] The term *master* is used in some technology contexts that do not refer to a relationship of control.
[src:modbus-protocol/slave-technology] *Master* may be used to mean a copy that has more significance than other copies, in which case the term is an absolute concept, not a relationship.
[src:modbus-protocol/slave-technology] Sometimes the term *master–slave* is used in contexts that do not imply a controlling relationship.
[src:modbus-protocol/slave-technology] In source code management *master* may refer to the trunk.
[src:modbus-protocol/slave-technology] In disk imaging, the gold master is the version that will be released to manufacturing for duplication.
[src:modbus-protocol/slave-technology] A Parallel ATA (aka IDE) hard drive interface supports two hard drives on a cable, which are designated *master* and *slave*.
[src:modbus-protocol/slave-technology] The distinction is required by the interface even though neither drive has control or priority over the other.
[src:modbus-protocol/slave-technology] The *master–slave* terminology was first used in 1904.
[src:modbus-protocol/slave-technology] The terminology was used in 1988 for RFC 1059 and in 1997 for RFC 2136, related to the domain name system.
[src:modbus-protocol/slave-technology] Said hydraulic brakes for the automotive industry were patented in 1917 by Malcolm Loughead.
[src:modbus-protocol/slave-technology] The term *slave cylinder* was used in other patent applications, including one by Robert Esnault-Pelterie, published in 1919.
[src:modbus-protocol/slave-technology] Media analytics company Global Language Monitor placed *master/slave* first in their annual list of politically charged language for 2004.
[src:modbus-protocol/slave-technology] The Black Lives Matter movement in the United States sparked renewed discussion, and terminology changes occurred in 2020.
[src:modbus-protocol/slave-technology] Some argued, however, that terminology changes were superficial or performative activism.
[src:modbus-protocol/slave-technology] In 2003, after receiving a discrimination complaint from a county employee, the County of Los Angeles in California asked that manufacturers, suppliers and contractors stop using *master* and *slave* terminology on products.
[src:modbus-protocol/slave-technology] Following complaints, the County of Los Angeles issued a statement saying that the decision was "nothing more than a request".
[src:modbus-protocol/slave-technology] In 2018, after a heated debate, developers of Python replaced the term.
[src:modbus-protocol/slave-technology] Depending on context, Python switched to *main*, *parent*, or *server* (in place of *master*), and *worker*, *child*, or *helper* (in place of *slave*).
[src:modbus-protocol/slave-technology] The Linux kernel adopted a similar policy to use more specific terms in new code and documentation.
[src:modbus-protocol/slave-technology] In July 2018, Google's developer style guide was updated to include avoiding the term *master* in software documentation, especially in combination with *slave.* Instead, the guide recommends terms – when in combination – such as *primary/secondary* and *original/replica*.
[src:modbus-protocol/slave-technology] Many individual variants of master and slave are given.
[src:modbus-protocol/slave-technology] In 2020, GitHub renamed the default *master* git branch to *main*.
